example.p:
Use this information to answer the following questions.








      Determine the fraction of callers who wait between 5 and 10 minutes.







      Next, let's study the fraction who wait up to a certain number of minutes:






            What is the fraction of callers who wait between 0 and 5 minutes?







            What is the fraction of callers who wait between 0 and 10 minutes?










      Let F(b) represent the fraction of callers who wait between 0 and b minutes.
      Find a formula for F(b) that involves a definite integral,
      and then use the First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus  to find a formula for F(b) that does not involve a definite integral.







      What is the value of the limit \lim\limits_{b \to \infty} F(b)?
      What is its meaning in the context of the problem?











        \int_5^{10} 0.25 e^{0.25t} \, dt = e^{-5/4} -e^{-10/4} \approx 0.2044







            1-e^{-5/4}\approx 0.7135



            1-e^{-10/4}\approx 0.9179





        F(b)=\int_0^b p(t) \, dt=1-e^{-b/4}



        \lim_{b \to \infty} F(b)=1


          The limit has the following meaning: All customers, or 100% of customers, have to wait at least 0 minutes.








    The general antiderivative of p(t) can be found by using the  substitution  u=-0.25t \ , du=-0.25 dt. Then \int p(t) \, dt= -e^{-0.25t} + C. We'll use the general antiderivative to efficiently find the definite integrals in parts (a), (b), (c), and (d). 




          \int_5^{10} 0.25 e^{0.25t} \, dt&=\left.\left(-e^{-t/4}\right) \right|_{5}^{10} 
           &=-e^{-10/4}+e^{-5/4}  
           &= e^{-5/4} -e^{-10/4} \approx 0.2044









              \int_{0}^{5} 0.25 e^{0.25t} \, dt&=\left.\left(-e^{-t/4}\right) \right|_{0}^{5} 
               &=-e^{-5/4}+e^{0/4}  
              &=1-e^{-5/4}\approx 0.7135





              \int_{0}^{10} 0.25 e^{0.25t} \, dt&=\left.\left(-e^{-t/4}\right) \right|_{0}^{10}
               &=-e^{-10/4}+e^{0/4}  
              &=1-e^{-10/4}\approx 0.9179








        F(b)=\int_0^b p(t) \, dt = \left.\left(-e^{-t/4}\right) \right|_{0}^{b}=1-e^{-b/4}





          \lim_{b \to \infty} F(b)&= \lim_{b \to \infty} \left(1-e^{-b/4} \right)
           &=1-\lim_{b \to \infty} e^{-b/4} 
          &=1-\lim_{b \to \infty} \frac{1}{e^{b/4}} 
          &=1 



          The limit has the following meaning: All customers, or 100% of customers, have to wait at least 0 minutes.

solution.p:
First, set up a limit to properly evaluate the improper integral. \int_1^{\infty} \frac{1}{x^p} \, dx = \lim_{b \to \infty} \int_1^b x^{-p} \, dx Notice that the antiderivative is different if p=1 or p \neq 1 , so we'll calculate these cases separately. Assume p\neq 1 .
\int_1^{\infty} \frac{1}{x^p} \, dx &= \lim_{b \to \infty} \int_1^b x^{-p} \, dx &= \lim_{b \to \infty} \left. \frac{x^{-p+1}}{-p+1} \right|_1^b &= \lim_{b \to \infty} \frac{b^{-p+1}}{-p+1} - \frac{1}{-p+1} &= -\frac{1}{-p+1} + \frac{1}{-p+1} \lim_{b \to \infty} b^{-p+1}
If -p+1 >0 (so p <1 ) then this limit diverges which implies that the improper integral diverges.

The integrand is undefined at x=0 , so we need to set up a limit that approaches 0 from the right for the lower bound of the integral. \int_0^1 \frac{1}{x^p} \, dx = \lim_{a \to 0^{+}} \int_a^1 x^{-p} \, dx The gereral antiderivative is different if p=1 or p \neq 1 , so we will handle each case separately. Assume p \neq 1 .
\int_0^1 \frac{1}{x^p} \, dx &= \lim_{a \to 0^{+}} \int_a^1 x^{-p} \, dx &= \lim_{a \to 0^{+}} \left. \frac{x^{-p+1}}{-p+1} \right| &= \lim_{a \to 0^{+}} \frac{1}{-p+1} - \frac{a^{-p+1}}{-p+1} &= \frac{1}{-p+1} -\frac{1}{-p+1} \lim_{a \to 0^{+}} a^{-p+1}
If -p+1>0 (so p< 1) then the limit converges so the improper integral converges.

Set up a limit to carefully calculate the improper integral. \int_0^{\infty} e^{-ax} \, dx = \lim_{b \to \infty} \int_0^b e^{-ax} \, dx The antiderivative is different if a=0 or if a \neq 0, so we'll calculate these cases separately. Assume a \neq 0 .
\int_0^{\infty} e^{-ax} \, dx &= \lim_{b \to \infty} \int_0^b e^{-ax} \, dx &= \lim_{b \to \infty} \left. -\frac{1}{a} e^{-ax} \right|_0^b &= -\frac{1}{a} \lim_{b \to \infty} \left( e^{-ab} -1 \right) &=\frac{1}{a} -\frac{1}{a} \lim_{b \to \infty} e^{-ab}
If -ab \lt 0 (so a\gt0), then the limit converges which implies the improper integral converges.

li.p:
If p \gt 1, then 1-p \lt 0 and
\frac{1}{1-p}\lim_{b \to \infty} \left( (\ln(b))^{1-p} - 1 \right) = \frac{1}{1-p}\lim_{b \to \infty} \left( \frac{1}{(\ln(b))^{p-1}} - 1 \right) = \left(\frac{1}{1-p}\right)(0-1) = \frac{1}{p-1}
In this case the improper integral \int_e^{\infty} \frac{1}{x(\ln(x))^p} \, dx converges to \frac{1}{p-1}.
